explanation: The solution uses a vector to store all the indices of the matrix. It shuffles this vector randomly and then uses it to pick a random index for flipping. The `flip` operation takes O(1) time as it simply removes and returns the last element of the vector. The `reset` operation takes O(m*n) time to rebuild the vector of indices. The space complexity is O(m*n) due to the storage of all indices. The energy implications are low as the algorithm does not involve any computationally expensive operations.

